[2] Liberia: new cases among health workers
Date: Wed 3 Dec 2014
Source: AllAfrica, The Inquirer (Monrovia) report [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201412031865.html


Liberia: 4 new Ebola cases among health workers
-----------------------------------------------
4 health workers in Montserrado County have been infected with the Ebola virus, the head of the Incident Management System (IMS), Tolbert Nyenswah, has disclosed. This brings to over 300 the number of Ebola infections in healthcare givers nationwide with more than 170 deaths, since the Ebola outbreak [was 1st reported] in March 2014, according to the Health Ministry Situational Report.

According to Nyenswah, the 4 health workers did not get infected at an Ebola Treatment Unit (ETU), but at private facilities or homes where they cared for suspected patients without proper use of personal protective equipment (PPE). "The new infections of these health workers should constitute a somber reminder to Liberians that ... people should stop playing doctor, but rather report all forms of illnesses to the hospital," he said. Nyenswah said the 4 are being treated at the US Army-run Monrovia Medical Unit (MMU) in Charlesville, Margibi County, set up specifically for health workers and foreign volunteers. The MMU, dedicated 5 Nov 2014, was financed by the American Government and built jointly by the United States Military and the Armed Forces of Liberia.

